  "description": "Add a new Microsoft Outlook integration.\n\nGreat question, Michael! Yes, you can absolutely build an app that reads Outlook.com (personal Microsoft account) emails. Given your recent work with Microsoft Graph and Azure AD, you're already on the right track. Here's the landscape:\n\n**Microsoft Graph API** is the way to do it. It provides unified access to Outlook.com mailboxes (personal Microsoft accounts) as well as Microsoft 365/Exchange mailboxes. The endpoint you'd use is `/me/messages` or `/me/mailFolders/{id}/messages`.\n\n**Key considerations for personal (consumer) accounts:**\n\nThe auth flow differs slightly from organizational (Azure AD) accounts. For personal Microsoft accounts, you need to use the **Microsoft identity platform v2.0 endpoint**, which supports both work/school and personal accounts. When registering your app in Azure portal, you'd select \"Accounts in any organizational directory and personal Microsoft accounts\" as the supported account type.\n\n**Delegated permissions** you'd typically request include `Mail.Read` or `Mail.ReadWrite`. The user signs in via OAuth 2.0 and consents to the scopes. This is essentially what you've been exploring with your Graph/Azure AD integration work — the main difference is ensuring your app registration supports the \"consumers\" or \"common\" tenant.\n\n**Auth flow options:**\n\nFor a server-side app or CLI tool, the **authorization code flow** works well. For a webhook-based ingestion pipeline (like you've been exploring), you can use **Graph subscriptions** to get notified of new messages, though there are some nuances with personal accounts — change notifications for personal mailboxes have historically had some limitations compared to M365 mailboxes.\n\n**Practical steps:**\n\n1. Register the app in Azure portal with multi-tenant + personal account support\n2. Configure redirect URIs for your auth flow\n3. Request `Mail.Read` (delegated) scope\n4. Use the `/common` or `/consumers` authority endpoint for token acquisition\n5. Call `https://graph.microsoft.com/v1.0/me/messages` with the bearer token\n\n**Watch out for:** Rate limits on personal accounts tend to be more restrictive than M365, and some Graph features (like rich filtering or extended properties) may behave differently on consumer mailboxes.\n\nWould you like me to help you scaffold something specific — like an auth flow, a webhook listener, or a quick prototype to pull messages?",
